value.value: Binding to a protein upon post-translation modification of the target protein.

definition.value: This term should only be used when the binding is shown to require a post-translational modification: the interaction needs to be tested with and without the PTM. The binding does not need to be at the site of the modification. It may be that the PTM causes a conformational change that allows binding of the protein to another region; this type of modification-dependent protein binding is valid for annotation to this term.

value.value: Binding to a protein upon methylation of the target protein.

definition.value: This term should only be used when the binding is shown to require methylation of the target protein: the interaction needs to be tested with and without the PTM. The binding does not need to be at the site of methylation. It may be that the methylation causes a conformational change that allows binding of the protein to another region; this type of methylation-dependent protein binding is valid for annotation to this term.

label.value: cell-cell adhesion in response to extracellular stimulus

value.value: The attachment of one cell to another cell via adhesion molecules as a result of an extracellular stimulus.
A process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts of a lipid droplet.

label.value: lipid droplet localization to prospore membrane leading edge

value.value: Any process in which a lipid droplet is transported to, or maintained to the prospore membrane leading edge.

The process in which a mitochondrial gene's sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.
The process by which an organelle membrane interacts with another membrane via molecular tethers that physically bridge the two membranes and attach them to each other.

Facilitating the removal of a protein or protein complex from a DNA molecule driven by ATP hydrolysis. This can be achieved for example by introducing non-canonical DNA structures or generating torque to directly inhibit a protein-DNA binding interaction.

label.value: catalytic activity, acting on a protein

value.value: Catalytic activity that acts to modify a protein.
Catalytic activity that acts to modify DNA.
Catalytic activity that acts to modify RNA, driven by ATP hydrolysis.

label.value: catalytic activity, acting on a tRNA

value.value: Catalytic activity that acts to modify a tRNA.

definition.value: Note that this term excludes activities for which a charged tRNA acts as an amino acid donor.

value.value: Directly binding to a specific ion or molecule and delivering it either to an acceptor molecule or to a specific location.

definition.value: Note that a carrier moves with its substrate/cargo, while a transporter does not move with the cargo, but facilitates the change in localization.

value.value: The directed movement of some substance from inside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the extracellular region.
Binding to and carrying a cargo between the nucleus and the cytoplasm by moving along with the cargo. The cargo can be either a RNA or a protein.

A cellular process in which two or more cells combine together, their plasma membrane fusing, producing a single cell. In some cases, nuclei fuse, producing a polyploid cell, while in other cases, nuclei remain separate, producing a syncytium.

label.value: regulation of cellular response to phosphate starvation

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to phosphate starvation.

label.value: negative regulation of cellular response to phosphate starvation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cellular response to phosphate starvation.
A contact site between the endoplasmic reticulum membrane and the plasma membrane, structured by bridging complexes.
The directed movement of hexose from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: repair of mitotic kinetochore microtubule attachment defect

value.value: The mitotic cell cycle process where kinetochore microtubule attachment defects are corrected.

label.value: repair of kinetochore microtubule attachment defect

value.value: The cell cycle process where kinetochore microtubule attachment defects are corrected.

The assembly and arrangement of a septum that spans the plasma membrane interface between progeny cells following mitotic cytokinesis. The progeny cells that form a division septum are not able to exchange intracellular material.

label.value: regulation of mitotic division septum assembly

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mitotic division septum formation. Division septum formation is the assembly and arrangement of a septum that spans the plasma membrane interface between progeny cells following cytokinesis.

label.value: negative regulation of mitotic division septum assembly

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of mitotic division septum formation. Division septum formation is the assembly and arrangement of a septum that spans the plasma membrane interface between progeny cells following cytokinesis.

label.value: positive regulation of mitotic division septum assembly

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mitotic division septum formation. Division septum formation is the assembly and arrangement of a septum that spans the plasma membrane interface between progeny cells following cytokinesis.

label.value: negative regulation of protein localization to medial cortex

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to the medial cortex.
The directed movement of some substance from a cell, into the extracellular region. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via exocytosis.

label.value: heme export from vacuole to cytoplasm

value.value: The directed movement of heme from inside the vacuole across the vacuolar membrane and into the cytosol.

Primary active transporter that auto-phosphorylates (hence P) at a key conserved aspartate residue, generating a conformational change that allows transport of the substrate. Hydrolysis of the phosphorylated Asp residue, catalyzed by the actuator (A) domain, results in another state with occluded substrates. Upon dissociation of Mg2+ and inorganic phosphate (Pi), the enzyme reverts to the initial state, in which the counter-transported substrate is released into the cytosol.

label.value: spindle pole body-led chromosome movement during mitotic interphase

value.value: A microtubule-based process in which chromosomes migrate as a result of rapid spindle pole body (SPB) and centrosome oscillations during mitotic interphase.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA alternative polyadenylation.

label.value: positive regulation of mRNA alternative polyadenylation

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA alternative polyadenylation.
The directed movement of a heme from outside of a cell into a cell. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

label.value: positive regulation of mitotic sister chromatid biorientation

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mitotic sister chromatid biorientation, the mitotic cell cycle process in which sister chromatids establish stable, end-on attachments to the plus ends of microtubules emanating from opposite spindle poles, oriented such that separation can proceed.

label.value: regulation of protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to a meiotic spindle pole body.

label.value: positive regulation of protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body

value.value: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to a meiotic spindle pole body.

label.value: negative regulation of protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein localization to a meiotic spindle pole body.
Reversible aggregate of misfolded proteins and chaperones formed to shield thermosensitive proteins from degradation until conditions allow disaggregation and refolding.
The reversible aggregation of misfolded proteins and chaperones, formed to shield thermosensitive proteins from degradation until conditions allow disaggregation and refolding.

label.value: initial meiotic spindle pole body separation

value.value: The release of duplicated meiotic spindle pole bodies (SPBs).
Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from a protein.

label.value: cell cortex of non-growing cell tip

value.value: The region directly beneath the plasma membrane at the cell tip at which no growth takes place.

label.value: mitotic spindle pole body insertion into the nuclear envelope

value.value: A process in which the duplicated mitotic spindle pole body is inserted into a fenestra which opens in the nuclear envelope in early mitosis, and is subsequently tethered to the membrane.
The action of a molecule that provides a shape or a sequence mimicking or complementary to the final product, providing template for copying the original molecule's shape or sequence.

label.value: negative regulation of mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of negative regulation of mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of reticulophagy.
Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of reticulophagy.

A stable assembly of two or more macromolecules, i.e. proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates or lipids, in which at least one component is a protein and the constituent parts function together in the nucleus.
A DNA recombination process that results in the bidirectional exchange of genetic material between highly homologous DNA molecules.
